    <node id="Generalized Hypergeometric Series _r F_s (equation)">
      <data key="d0">Generalized Hypergeometric Series _r F_s (equation)</data>
      <data key="d1">equation</data>
      <data key="d2">This equation defines the generalized hypergeometric series, a cornerstone of special function theory relating to basic hypergeometric series through q-analogue relationships. It represents the classical limit form (q→1) discussed in the broader context involving Campbell-Cantarini techniques and Yamaguchi's q-analogues. The equation appears in contexts discussing summation by parts, Abel lemmas, and constructions of q-analogues throughout Sections 2.1–2.3. It connects fundamental mathematical objects including Pochhammer symbols, factorials, and convergence theory for infinite series.</data>
      <data key="d3">chunk-8c9ae39fd997800b42912e965bb0c5b1</data>
      <data key="d4">math1.pdf</data>
      <data key="d5">1774687308</data>
    </node>
    <node id="q-Shifted Factorial Definitions (equation)">
      <data key="d0">q-Shifted Factorial Definitions (equation)</data>
      <data key="d1">equation</data>
      <data key="d2">This equation defines the q-shifted factorial (q-Pochhammer symbol), a fundamental construct in q-calculus and basic hypergeometric series theory. The three-part definition establishes normalization, finite products, and infinite products for the q-deformation of factorials. These expressions serve as the primary notation for basic hypergeometric series _rφ_s in Bailey's framework. Under the assumption that |q| &lt; 1, these q-shifted factorials converge appropriately and relate to classical shifted factorials through a q→1 limit. This foundational definition enables the construction of q-analogues of classical identities (including Yamaguchi's q-analogue of Gosper's identity), facilitates the modified Abel lemma approach for summation by parts, and provides notation essential for research in combinatorics, special functions, mathematical physics, and quantum algebraic structures involving q-deformation of gamma, beta functions, theta functions, and vertex operators.</data>
      <data key="d3">chunk-7cd8341404d2b69d98c8961756f7fbef</data>
      <data key="d4">math1.pdf</data>
      <data key="d5">1774687308</data>
    </node>
    <node id="Basic Hypergeometric Series ${}_{r}\\phi_{r-1}$ (equation)">
      <data key="d0">Basic Hypergeometric Series ${}_{r}\\phi_{r-1}$ (equation)</data>
      <data key="d1">equation</data>
      <data key="d2">This equation defines the basic hypergeometric series of type ${}_{r}\\phi_{r-1}$, a q-analogue of the classical generalized hypergeometric series. It serves as a fundamental building block in q-series theory, combinatorics, and mathematical physics. The series incorporates q-shifted factorials and converges when the base parameter satisfies |q|&lt;1. In the surrounding context, it represents a key construction for deriving q-analogues of classical identities, connecting research on summation by parts techniques, Abel lemmas, and the work of multiple researchers in q-calculus including Bailey, Chu, Campbell, and Cantarini. This framework enables the formulation of q-analogues of combinatorial identities including Gosper's identity.</data>
      <data key="d3">chunk-753ef89544f7e74a4ea66a0fe087afb3</data>
      <data key="d4">math1.pdf</data>
      <data key="d5">1774687308</data>
    </node>
    <node id="Generalized q-Shifted Factorial Product Notation (equation)">
      <data key="d0">Generalized q-Shifted Factorial Product Notation (equation)</data>
      <data key="d1">equation</data>
      <data key="d2">This equation defines a generalized notation for representing ratios of q-shifted factorials in basic hypergeometric series theory. It consolidates multiple q-Pochhammer symbols into a compact form useful for q-calculus computations and analysis. The notation enables systematic representation of terms in _rφ_{s-1} basic hypergeometric series, facilitating q-analogue constructions and summation identities. Essential to q-series theory and combinatorial analysis, this definition connects classical factorial theory to q-deformations while maintaining the limit relationship to classical mathematics as q → 1.</data>
      <data key="d3">chunk-d128add90e7f551a5bf0aa11f3f4b9a6</data>
      <data key="d4">math1.pdf</data>
      <data key="d5">1774687308</data>
    </node>
    <node id="Infinite q-Shifted Factorial Product Ratio (q-Hypergeometric Series Notation) (equation)">
      <data key="d0">Infinite q-Shifted Factorial Product Ratio (q-Hypergeometric Series Notation) (equation)</data>
      <data key="d1">equation</data>
      <data key="d2">The equation defines the standard notation for infinite q-shifted factorial products in basic hypergeometric series theory. This fundamental identity expresses a ratio of q-Pochhammer symbol products, serving as the building block for q-hypergeometric series _rphi_s-1. The notation connects classical combinatorial shifted factorials through the q→1 limit, establishing it as a genuine q-analogue. This definition is crucial for constructing q-analogues of classical identities using techniques by Campbell and Cantarini. The equation establishes the notation used throughout Sections 2.1-2.3 for general q-series manipulation, hypergeometric transformations, and applications in quantum algebra, combinatorics, and statistical mechanics contexts involving q-deformed systems.</data>
      <data key="d3">chunk-836cf962849916c948ed658a5e3aca76</data>
      <data key="d4">math1.pdf</data>
      <data key="d5">1774687308</data>
    </node>
    <node id="Modified Abel Lemma (equation)">
      <data key="d0">Modified Abel Lemma (equation)</data>
      <data key="d1">equation</data>
      <data key="d2">Equation (3) is the Modified Abel Lemma, a discrete calculus identity derived from summation by parts principles adapted for infinite series in $q$-calculus. It relates weighted backward differences to forward differences and boundary limits, specifically defined with non-standard signs for the $\Delta$ operator ($\tau_n - \tau_{n+1}$). This lemma is a primary tool constructed via Campbell and Cantarini methods to derive new $q$-analogues of classical identities (such as Gosper's), serving as a foundational mechanism for proving results in basic hypergeometric series contexts where standard telescoping sums are insufficient.</data>
      <data key="d3">chunk-948f619adaa6af7493a36bc96cd93d44</data>
      <data key="d4">math1.pdf</data>
      <data key="d5">1774687308</data>
    </node>
    <node id="A Further $q$-Analogue of Gosper’s Strange Series (header)">
      <data key="d0">A Further $q$-Analogue of Gosper’s Strange Series (header)</data>
      <data key="d1">header</data>
      <data key="d2">This header introduces the section dedicated to deriving a specific extension of Gosper’s Strange Series within the context of $q$-calculus. It acts as a structural divider following the theoretical preliminaries on hypergeometric series and the modified Abel lemma. The content focuses on establishing a new, inequivalent $q$-analogue of Gosper’s identity, distinct from Yamaguchi’s existing analogue. This section likely encompasses the core proof and application of the techniques referenced in the introduction, serving as a key entry point for researchers studying summation identities and $q$-series transformations in combinatorics.</data>
      <data key="d3">chunk-3b543e65153eeae6b53b00ef9af95c9e</data>
      <data key="d4">math1.pdf</data>
      <data key="d5">1774687308</data>
    </node>
    <node id="Section 2: Main Results (page_number)">
      <data key="d0">Section 2: Main Results (page_number)</data>
      <data key="d1">page_number</data>
      <data key="d2">Page 2 marks the beginning of Section 2, containing the paper's main results including a simplified proof of Yamaguchi's q-analogue using Campbell-Cantarini technique with modified Abel lemma, plus a new q-analogue of Gosper's identity. This section serves as the core contribution following Section 2.1-2.3 which demonstrates broader applications in q-analogue construction methodology.</data>
      <data key="d3">chunk-3dc45713b7a08b7ee7adcba0d112e701</data>
      <data key="d4">math1.pdf</data>
      <data key="d5">1774687308</data>
    </node>
    <node id="Q-Shifted Factorials">
      <data key="d0">Q-Shifted Factorials</data>
      <data key="d1">concept</data>
      <data key="d2">Q-Shifted Factorials are a cornerstone construct in the theory of q-calculus and basic hypergeometric series, representing the q-analogue of the classical shifted factorial.&lt;SEP&gt;Mathematical constructs defined in Section 1 and utilized in the main body of the paper.&lt;SEP&gt;Q-Shifted Factorials is a mathematical concept covered in the Section 1.1 preliminaries.</data>
      <data key="d3">chunk-7cd8341404d2b69d98c8961756f7fbef&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-3b543e65153eeae6b53b00ef9af95c9e&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-3dc45713b7a08b7ee7adcba0d112e701</data>
      <data key="d4">math1.pdf</data>
      <data key="d5">1774688568</data>
      <data key="d6" />
    </node>
    <node id="Q-Calculus">
      <data key="d0">Q-Calculus</data>
      <data key="d1">concept</data>
      <data key="d2">Q-Calculus is a theoretical framework where q-shifted factorials serve as fundamental constructs and where limit expressions converge.&lt;SEP&gt;The field of study within which this formula is situated and used.&lt;SEP&gt;The mathematical field involving summation by parts used in the proofs referenced.</data>
      <data key="d3">chunk-7cd8341404d2b69d98c8961756f7fbef&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-948f619adaa6af7493a36bc96cd93d44&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-3b543e65153eeae6b53b00ef9af95c9e</data>
      <data key="d4">math1.pdf</data>
      <data key="d5">1774688568</data>
      <data key="d6" />
    </node>
    <node id="Basic Hypergeometric Series">
      <data key="d0">Basic Hypergeometric Series</data>
      <data key="d1">concept</data>
      <data key="d2">Basic Hypergeometric Series is a mathematical area in which q-shifted factorials play a cornerstone role within q-calculus.&lt;SEP&gt;A fundamental mathematical construct defined by an infinite sum of q-shifted factorials, serving as a cornerstone in q-calculus.&lt;SEP&gt;A mathematical context in which the notation extends the standard Bailey shifted factorial formalism to accommodate multiple parameters.&lt;SEP&gt;The theory related to the context where the formula is applied.&lt;SEP&gt;Basic Hypergeometric Series is a mathematical concept detailed within the preliminaries section.</data>
      <data key="d3">chunk-7cd8341404d2b69d98c8961756f7fbef&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-948f619adaa6af7493a36bc96cd93d44&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-d128add90e7f551a5bf0aa11f3f4b9a6&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-753ef89544f7e74a4ea66a0fe087afb3&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-3dc45713b7a08b7ee7adcba0d112e701</data>
      <data key="d4">math1.pdf</data>
      <data key="d5">1774688570</data>
      <data key="d6" />
    </node>
    <node id="Classical Shifted Factorial">
      <data key="d0">Classical Shifted Factorial</data>
      <data key="d1">concept</data>
      <data key="d2">Classical Shifted Factorial is the standard Pochhammer symbol limit to which q-shifted factorials converge when q approaches 1.</data>
      <data key="d3">chunk-7cd8341404d2b69d98c8961756f7fbef</data>
      <data key="d4">math1.pdf</data>
      <data key="d5">1774688570</data>
      <data key="d6" />
    </node>
    <node id="Pochhammer Symbol">
      <data key="d0">Pochhammer Symbol</data>
      <data key="d1">concept</data>
      <data key="d2">The Pochhammer symbol (a)_n represents the shifted factorial defined as x(x+1)...(x+n-1) for positive integers n.&lt;SEP&gt;Pochhammer Symbol is the resulting standard expression obtained from q-shifted factorials as q approaches 1 and n divided by powers of (1-q).</data>
      <data key="d3">chunk-7cd8341404d2b69d98c8961756f7fbef&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-8c9ae39fd997800b42912e965bb0c5b1</data>
